{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937111901/0606.xml":{"full_text":"China Getting British Arms,\nJapanese Officials Charge\nBy United Press 4\nTOK 10, Nov. 19 \u2014China is receiving important\nquantities of war munitions thru Hong Kong, British\nstrategic base off the south China coast, Japanese\nauthorities asserted today.\nBoth the War Office and the\nForeign Office possess definite\ninformation that the shipments\nhave been made, it was said. It\nwas indicated that shipments\nwere going direct to Hong\nKong, from Great Britain and\nother countries and that in ad\ndition some were reaching\nHong Kong by way of French\nIndo-China.\nA Foreign Office spokesman in\ntimated that the Japanese blockade\nof the Chinese coast was effective, so\nfar as shipments direct to China were\nconcerned.\nAn American, arriving here from\nHong Kong, said it was common\nknowledge that large shipments from\nmany sources were reaching the Chi\nnese forces thru British territory.\nThese arms, the informant said, were\nsent on from Hong Kong to Canton\nand thence along the railroad to\nHankow.\nThe Japanese navy and air force,\nthe informant said, were doing all\nthey could to intercept such ship\nments as were liable to seizure un\nder international law.\nGunboat Reaches Nanking\nBy United Press\nSHANGHAI, Nov. 19\u2014The United\nStates gunboat Luzon arrived at Nan\nking today after a full-steam race\nfrom Hankow to embark American\nAmbassador Nelson T. Johnson and\nhis staff.\nJohnson, like other diplomats, in\ntends to evacuate the capital and\nmove up the Yangtze River to Han\nkow, where the Chinese government\nis to establish emergency headquar\nters in view of the danger of a Jap\nanese thrust at Nanking.\nThe government delayed its formal\nannouncement of its departure but i\nthe evacuation was speeded daily, i\nThousands of civilians crowded the\nwaterfront and the railroad stations\nin the mud and rain. I\nASKS REFUGE\nAt the request of foreign mission\naries, Ambassador Johnson commu\nnicated to Japanese authorities re\ngarding a refugee camp which has\nbeen established near Soochow, next\nobjective of the Japanese drive west\nward from Shanghai. It ws under\nstood that he asked the Japanese to\nissue orders that safety of refugees\nshould be assured.\nFor the third day rain grounded\nJapanese airplanes.\nBut on the\nground, slithering thru the mud west\nof Shanghai, Japanese troops con\ntinued their relentless drive on the\ndisorganized Chinese army.\nA Japanese spokesman announced\nthat at dawn today the Japanese\noccupied Changshu and completed\ntheir smashing of the Fushan-Chang\nshu line of defense extending from\nthe Yangtze River bank southward\ntoward Soochow. At the same time,\nthe spokesman said, Japanese stormed\nand\ntook\nYushan,\nnorthwest of\nChangshu, and Mocheng, southwest\n5-Day Week is Urged\nfor U. S. Employes\ni Sentiment crystallized on Capitol\ni Hill today to givn Federal and Dis\ni trict employes a new deal by cutting\ntheir work week, providing for over\ntime compensation and setting up an\nagency for hearing grievances.\nTwo bills were introduced late yes\nterday in the House and at least one\nother was being prepared seeking to\ni benefit Federal workers, while in the\nI Senate a resolution was offered by\nI\nj Sen. Ellender <D., La.) proposing an\ninquiry of the Civil Service Commis\nsion.\nIn introducing the resolution\nSen. Ellender invited Civil Service\nworkers to report to him cases of al\nleged favoritism or discrimination.\nRep. John McCormack (D., Mass.)\nintroduced a bill providing for a five\nday work week for all Federal em\nployes and time and a half for over- i\ntime work for employes making less\nthan $3200 annually.\nThe employe would have his choice\nof compensatory leave or cash for\novertime. Overtime would be de\ntermined by the Budget Bureau for i\nold-line agencies and by a special\nboard for independent agencies. i\nEmploye grievances would be ap\npealed to a referee appointed by the\nCivil Service Commission under a\nHouse bill sponsored by Rep. Bige\nlow (D., O.).\nRep. Randolph (D., W. Va.) today\ncalled upon the Civil Service Com\nmission to cease its discrimination\nagainst persons more than 45 years\nof age seeking certain Government\npositions.\nRandolph, a member of\nthe House Civil Service Committee,\nis preparing a bill to that effect.\nSimpsons Seek Seclusion\non Vermont Wedding Trip\nBRDGEPORT. Conn., Nov. 19\u2014Ern- i\nest L. Simpson and his bride were on i\na motor honeymoon in New England I\ntoday, seeking seclusion after a wed-\n10 -v- \u2014111 1 41 i\nding ceremony which united the\nBritish ship broker and the woman\nwho introduced him to his second\nwife, now the Duchess of 'indsor.\nSimpson and the former Mrs. Mary\nKirk Rraffray planned to spend a\nfew days in Vermont before returning\nto New York. They were scheduled\nto sail for London Dec. 10.\nMrs. Rraffray obtained a Reno di\nvorce from Jacques A. L. Rraffray,\nNew York broker, last week. Probate\nJudge Bradford Boardman at Fair- j\nfield waived Connecticut\u2019s five-day\nwaiting law and the blood test re-\nquirement to permit the couple to be i\nmarried yesterday. i\nI\n\u2014News-Acme l\nDR. ALLAN ROY DAFOE, physician for the Dfonne babies, i\nwas caught in this unusual portrait during a recent visit i\nto New York.\nAldrich Asks Repeal\nof \u2018Hampering\u2019 Laws\nBy United Press\nNEW YORK, Nov. 19\u2014Leading\nbankers and industrialists, blaming\nthe current business\nrecession\non\npolitics of the Roosevelt Administra\ntion. today advanced a \u201crepeal and\nmodification\" program which they\nclaimed would bring recovery.\nTheir spokesman was Winthrop W.\nAldrich, chairman of the board of\nthe Chase National Bank, who de\nclared that \"if the existing laws which\nhamper business recovery should be\npromptly\nrepealed\nor\nadequately\nmodified. the automatic result would\nbe that industrial production would\nincrease and that the existing busi\nness depression would be checked\u2014\na result which would benefit every\nmember of the community.\u201d\nAldrich demanded a return to the\ngold standard, a balanced budget,\nrepeal of the undistributed profits\ntax, modification of the capital gains\ntax and the freeing of public utilities\nfrom Government competition.\nHe\ndeclared that a balanced budget was\nthe chief factor, and that if the\nTreasury reached that goal, \"the cor\nnerstone of the foundation of true\nbusiness recovery will have been laid.\"\nI Aldrich addressed the 16th annual\ndinner meeting of the New York State\nChamber of Commerce, of which he\nis president, and in the audience of\n800 were many of the nation's bank\ning, industrial and business leaders.\nFilipinos Count Typhoon Dead\nMANILA P. I.. Nov. 19\u2014Belated\nreports of a typhoc\nwhich swept\nthru the southern part of the Philip\npine archipelago listed 26 persons\ndead tonight and news of widespread\nhavoc trickled in from the distressed\nareas. A state of emergency was de\ncreed on the island of Leyte. threat\nened by a serious food shortage.\nRestoring of Business Confidence\nNeeded to Halt New Depression,\nSays Head of Brookings\nI\nI\nSlumps and booms are pretty much a matter of psychology, says Gen.\nJohnson in his column on Page 23.\nBy MAX STERN\nThe 1937 \u201crecession\u201d has a 50-50 chance of becoming\ni the 1937 depression, and a quick restoration of business\ni confidence is the key to the problem, according to Dr.\nHarold G. Moulton, president of Brookings Institution.\nIn an interview today Dr. Moulton said he regarded\nPresident Roosevelt\u2019s message to Congress as a restora\ntive influence, and listed the following possible steps\nhe considered \u201chelpful\u201d in restoring recovery\u2019s tempo:\n1 AAA1 f ino IAA AF +$1-- .*=***.*4 A\nI I. Modification of the undistribut-1\n1 ed-profits and capital-gains taxes.\nsince\nI He does not regard changes in mon\netary controls as important, since\nmoney is not tight at present.\n2. Balancing the Federal budget, a\nmeasure that is \"fundamentally im\nportant from the standpoint of sta\ni bility.\u201d\n1 3. Emphasis on expansion in the\ndurable-goods field, with particular\nstress on making the way easier for\nlarge-scale home building and con\nstruction and for modernization pro\ngrams in the utilities fields.\nMUST REVIVE CONFIDENCE\n\u201cWhether the present recession\nsinks deeper and becomes a major\ndepression depends, I believe, on the\ndegree of confidence that can be re\nstored within the next two or three\nmonths,\u201d said the head of the great\nresearch foundation.\n\u201cThere are psychological as well\nas economic factors to deal with. If\nconfidence is restored and business\nundertakes long-term commitments\nwe may look for a quick recovery; if\nconfidence continues at its present\ni low ebb the recession may become\nserious indeed.\u201d\nSpeaking of ways to make building\nconstruction easier, he urged \"high\naggregate\u201d or annual wages for la\nbor instead of the present high wage\nrates and seasonal unemployment.\nI Building materials are still high but\nare declining, he said.\n\"If the building industry were so\norganized as to permit employment\non an annual, instead of an hourly\nor daily basis, labor costs might be\nreduced without reducing earnings,\"\nhe continued. \u201cIndeed, with lower\ncosts, production might be expanded\nand aggregate earnings greatly in\nNews-Acme\nPROOF HE WAS RICH got Sam Velcich, 51-year-old nomad,\nout of a tough spot when arrested by New Orleans police.\nBut Sam said he wasn\u2019t, and\nThey said he was a vagrant.\npulled forth $6000 worth of bonds which produced a revenue\nof $91 a month. Down and out several times, Veleich for\nmerly worked for a power company which issued the bonds.\ncreased.\nToday annual building\ntrades wages are pitiably low, due\npartly to high hourly wage rates and\npartly to irregular employment.\u201d\nDr. Moulton attributed the present\nrecession to a sudden maladjustment\nlast summer in the price-cost-wage\nstructure. Up to the end of 1936. he\nsaid, basic industrial trends were\ndistinctly favorable to recovery. Prices\nof manufactured goods were practi\ncally stable, while productive effi\nciency and wage rates were expand\ning.\nThus real purchasing power\nwas increasing.\nIn the autumn of 1936 prices of\nraw and manufactured goods started\nup as a result of foreign buying and\ndomestic expansion.\nEarly in 1937\nthere were \"abrupt\" wage increases.\n1 ranging from 20 per cent to 30 per\ncent, without corresponding increases\nin efficiency.\nThe sharply advanc\ning prices of steel and other products\nhit the railroads\u2019 expansion program,\nchecked home building and otherwise\ninterrupted the gradual expansion of\nthe national income.\nF. D. NAMES ECONOMIST\nENVOY TO SOUTH POLE\nHerbert M.\nBratter,\neconomic\nwriter, was appointed \"Ambassador\nto the South Pole\" by President\nRoosevelt today.\nBratter asked for the President\u2019s\nautograph under a note that read:\n\u201cI hereby appoint Herbert M. Brat\ni ter to be Ambassador to the North\nThe\ni Pole.\" The President, smiling.\nI struck out \u201cnorth\u201d and substituted\n/\u2019south.\u201d then signed his initials.\nP\nStrike Closes Plants\nof Goodyear Tire Co.\nAKRON. O., Nov. 19\u2014Goodyear\nTire\nRubber Co.'s two plants were\nclosed by a sit-down strike called by\nthe United Rubber Workers of Amer\nica. a Committee for Industrial Or\nganization union. Nearly 12,000 work\ners were idle.\nUnion officials estimted 1000 strik\ners were in the plants. Company\nexecutives did not comment.\nThe strike was the result of union\ndissatisfaction\nwith the company\u2019s\nrecent policy of layoffs. It began in\nthe tire production rooms shortly\nafter the midnight shift of workeis\nentered\nquickly.\nthe plants.\nand\nspread\nTen policemen were assigned\nto\nguard each plant. They said there\nwas no indication of disorder. Strik\ners did not attempt to organize\npickets.\nThe company had announced that\nbecause of a business recession. be\ntween 1500 and 2000 workers would\nbe laid off in addition to 1+00 dis\nmissed recently.\nIndex to Today\u2019s News\nBroun\nClapper\nomics\nCrossword Puzzle\nEditorials\nErnie Pyle\nGen. Johnson\nJohn T. Flynn\nS to 4:30\nRadio\nMrs. Roosevelt\nShort Story\n\u201cSide Glances\u201d\nSociety\nSports\nSerial Story\nTalburt's Cartoon\nTheaters\nWomen\u2019s Pages\n25\n25\n47\n28\n24, 25\n23\n23\n25\n6\n26\n23\n34\n.25\n33\n38. 38, 10\n_ 28\n24\n36, 37\n30. 22","height":"21012","width":"14572"}}
